1. Write a program to access a method and variable without creating object. Explain the steps
We are creating a method and variable and we are calling them without object creation because o using satic keyword in it.
package Program1;
import java.util.*;
class Students{ 
	static int a; // static variable
	public static void PrintName(String Name) {    //method called and executed
		System.out.println("Your name is : "+Name);
	}
	public static String ShowDepartment(String Department) { //we are using return type as string so it will return string value.
		return Department;
	}
}
public class WithoutObj {
	public static void main(String[] args) {
		Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);	
		String Name = sc.nextLine();    // getting input from the user
		String Department = sc.nextLine();
		Students.a = sc.nextInt(); 
		Students.PrintName(Name);   // calling the method using class name
		System.out.println("Your Department is : "+Students.ShowDepartment(Department));
		System.out.println("Your Roll No is : "+Students.a);  // printing the static variable.
			sc.close();
	}
}

2. Write a program to implement abstract class and method
package Program1;
import java.util.*;
abstract class Parent {
    abstract void Name(String name);
    abstract void PassWord(int passcode);
}
class Child extends Parent {   
    void Name(String name) {
        System.out.println("Your name is : " + name);
    }
    void PassWord(int passcode) {
        System.out.println("Your Passcode is : " + passcode);   
    }
}
class Abstraction {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        String name = sc.nextLine();
        int passcode = sc.nextInt();
        Child obj = new Child();
        obj.Name(name);
        obj.PassWord(passcode);
        sc.close();
    }
}

3. What is Multiple Inheritance? Explain with examples.
Multiple inheritance is a OOPs concept which is achieved by interface concept because java doesnot provide multiple inheritance due to ambiguity.
import java.util.*;
interface InterfaceProgram {
    void dog(); 
    void cat();
    default void snake() { 
        System.out.println("shhhhh...");
    }
}
interface InterfaceProgram1 {
    void tiger();
}
class Child implements InterfaceProgram, InterfaceProgram1 {
    public void dog() { 
        System.out.println("Barking...");
    }
    
    public void cat() {
        System.out.println("meowww...");
    }
    
    public void tiger() {
        System.out.println("hororr....");
    }
}
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Child obj = new Child();
        
        obj.dog();
        obj.cat();
        obj.snake();
        obj.tiger();
    }
}
